{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508152"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:02:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:02:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2720"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2720"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.01,0.84,0.04,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44663"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2720"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29545"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"3052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3436"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42557"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44663"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is brought to the Emergency Department after her husband became concerned that she was having difficulty walking and appeared confused over the last day. She has a medical history of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease, Grave\u0027s disease and a Roux-en-y gastric bypass four years ago. Her medications include carbimazole and atorvastatin. She is a non-smoker and says she drinks one to two standard drinks each night with occasional alcohol free days.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her vitals are within normal limits. She is not orientated to time or place and appears slightly drowsy intermittently. She is unable to walk. She has impaired lateral gaze and has nystagmus when looking horizontally. Upward gaze is preserved. Facial sensation is intact bilaterally, and there is no dysarthria. In her upper and lower limbs, her power is intact bilaterally and reflexes are symmetrical and she has no sensory deficits. However she has marked incoordination and ataxia of her upper limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Given the most likely diagnosis, what is the first step to manage this condition acutely?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV acyclovir","IV antibiotics","IV thiamine","IV midazolam","IV glucose"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with acute confusion. Combined with the clinical features of ataxia, horizontal nystagmus and ophthalmoplegia,\u00a0\u003Cem\u003EWernicke\u0027s encephalopathy\u003C/em\u003E\u00a0(WE) needs to be suspected. WE is an acute rapid onset brain syndrome secondary to thiamine (vitamin B1) deficiency. Thiamine has many roles but primarily acts as a co-enzyme in the Krebs\u0027 cycle. On the history alone, it is very likely that this patient has a thiamine deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECauses of thiamine deficiency include reduced intake (commonly in alcoholics and extreme dieting), decreased intestinal absorption (gastric bypass, gastrointestinal disease), increased consumption (hyperthyroidism, pregnancy), increased depletion (diarrhoea, furosemide use), severe liver disease, and co-existing folate deficiency. In this case, this patient may well drink more than she would care to admit, and her gastric bypass surgery will have impaired absorption of many materials, particularly thiamine. It is common practice for patients to under-report their smoking and drinking habits when quizzed by their medical practitioner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThiamine deficiency requires urgent treatment with\u003Cstrong\u003E intravenous thiamine \u003C/strong\u003E(oral thiamine has poor bioavailability). Early treatment can reverse WE. Once this has occurred then treating the underlying cause becomes the focus of management. It is important to note that there is a theoretical risk of worsening WE if glucose is given prior to thiamine (glucose metabolism uses up the remaining thiamine).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcyclovir\u003C/strong\u003E should be given empirically if encephalitis was suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E should be given empirically if meningitis was suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMidazolam\u003C/strong\u003E should be given if a status epilepticus was suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose\u003C/strong\u003E should be given if hypoglycaemia is was suspected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["For patients presenting with the triad of 1) acute confusional state, 2) ophthalmoplegia/nystagmus, 3) ataxia, think Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy."],"references":["Chang HW, Yang PY, Han T, Meng NH. Wernicke encephalopathy\u00a0concurrent with polyradiculoneuropathy in a young man after bariatric surgery A case report. Medicine. 2019;98(10). Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6417542/","NIckson, C. Thiamine deficiency. In: Life in the Fast Lane [online]. 2020 Nov 3 [cited 2021 Aug 3]. Available at: https://litfl.com/thiamine-deficiency/.","Swaminathan A. Wernicke Encephalopathy. In: REBEL EM [online]. 2018 [cited 2021 Aug 3]. Available at: https://rebelem.com/wernicke-encephalopathy/.","Ventura A, Mafe MC, Bourguet M, Tornero C. Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy secondary to hyperthyroidism and ingestion of thiaminase-rich products. Neurolog\u00eda. 2013;28(4):257-259. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22436368/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29545"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2720"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29545"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-26T10:18:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-26T10:18:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2720"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44663"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"3052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3052"},"attributes